# Unreliable Voices

![Lesson image for Unreliable Voices](https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Edgar_Allan_Poe_house_in_Baltimore.jpg)

Many Poe narrators speak with confidence while revealing fear, obsession, or contradiction. Readers must distinguish a narrator’s claim from the story’s evidence.

An unreliable narrator is not simply a narrator who lies. The term describes a gap between what a speaker claims and what the text gives readers reason to believe. Poe’s narrators may insist on their sanity, precision, or moral innocence while their word choices, omissions, repetitions, and actions create another pattern. The tension produces psychological pressure because readers must interpret the evidence without an external judge explaining everything.

A careful reading asks three questions. What does the narrator directly observe? What does the narrator infer? What does the narrator avoid or reinterpret? Those questions separate event from explanation. In “The Tell-Tale Heart,” for example, the narrator’s confidence does not erase the evidence of obsession. In “The Black Cat,” confession does not guarantee a stable account of responsibility.

Poe’s technique remains influential because it turns narration into a problem. The reader is not only asking what happened; the reader is evaluating the instrument that reports what happened. That is a useful skill beyond literature: sources, witnesses, interfaces, and persuasive arguments all have points of view.

> **Source and image note.** This lesson was prepared from [the linked research source](https://poemuseum.org/poes-complete-works/). The image is a separate visual primary-source or historical illustration prompt; examine what it shows, what it leaves out, and who made or preserved it.

